levised address, Boris Johnson announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the coronavirus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=Boris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| work=The Guardian| date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*24 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The UK records its highest number of coronavirus deaths in one day, after another 87 people die across the country, bringing the total to 422.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-calls-for-police-at-stations-after-packed-trains-defy-lockdown-11962837|title=Coronavirus: Biggest daily rise in UK deaths \u2013 up by 87 to 422\n| publisher=Sky News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: For the first time, all of the UK's [[List of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile networks]] send out a government text alert, ordering people to stay at home. The message reads: \"''GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives.''\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451|title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Secretary of State for Health|Health secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announces the government will open a temporary hospital, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]] at the [[Excel London]], to add extra critical care capacity in response to coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477|title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*25 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Prince Charles]] tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845|title=Coronavirus: Prince Charles tests positive but 'remains in good health'| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] shuts down for a month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52032188|title=Coronavirus: Parliament shuts down for a month| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[British Transport Police]] deploys 500 officers to patrol the UK's rail network, in an effort to discourage non-essential journeys. New measures are also introduced on the [[London Underground]] to reduce passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52023580|title=Coronavirus: New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential journeys| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*26 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces that the [[Self-employment|self-employed]] will be paid 80% of profits, up to \u00a32,500 a month, to help them cope during the economic crisis triggered by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52053914|title=Coronavirus: UK government unveils aid for self-employed| publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2020| accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: At 8pm, millions of people around the country take part in a \"[[Clap for our Carers]]\" tribute, applauding the NHS and other care workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52058013|title=Clap for Carers: UK in 'emotional' tribute to NHS and care workers| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The gesture is repeated every Thursday during the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>[https://clapforourcarers.co.uk/ Clap for our Carers every Thursday at 8pm #clapforourcarers]. Clap for our Carers.</ref>\n*27 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson tests positive for COVID-19, and will self-isolate in [[10 Downing Street]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] tests positive for COVID-19 and reports that he is working from home and self-isolating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-matt-hancock-boris-johnson-test-positive-covid-19-symptoms-a9430031.html|title=Coronavirus: Health secretary Matt Hancock tests positive| work=The Independent| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A significant rise in [[anxiety]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among the UK population is reported following the lockdown. The study, by researchers from the [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Ulster University]], finds that people reporting anxiety increased from 17% to 36%, while those reporting depression increased from 16% to 38%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/rise-in-depression-and-anxiety-day-after-uk-lockdown-announced-study-coronavirus |title=Rise in depression and anxiety day after UK lockdown announced \u2013 study| work=The Guardian| date=31 March 2020| accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April\n**The [[contactless payment]] limit for in-store spending is raised from \u00a330 to \u00a345.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2020/mar/24/limit-for-contactless-spending-to-rise-to-45-at-beginning-of-april|title=Limit for contactless spending to rise to \u00a345 at beginning of April|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK's [[National Living Wage]] rises from \u00a38.21 to \u00a38.72, an increase of 6.2%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/money/minimum-wage-increase-2020-april-rise-new-national-living-uk-pay-when-change-date-1352523|title=Minimum wage increase April 2020: what the new UK national living wage is and who gets a pay rise today|publisher=I News|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], the first temporary critical care hospital to treat COVID-19 patients, opens at the [[ExCeL London|ExCel centre]] in East London, employing NHS staff and military personnel, with a bed capacity of up to 4,000. It is the first of several [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|temporary critical care hospitals]] planned across the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598|title=Coronavirus: Nightingale Hospital opens at London's ExCel centre|work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*4 April \u2013 The results of the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] and the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] are announced, in which [[Keir Starmer]] is elected as the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], succeeding [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and [[Angela Rayner]] is elected as deputy leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*5 April\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes a [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|rare broadcast to the UK]] and the wider Commonwealth, something she has done on only four previous occasions. In the address she thanks people for following the government's social distancing rules and pays tribute to key workers, and says the UK \"will succeed\" in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/queen-to-address-nation-on-sunday-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Queen to address nation on Sunday over coronavirus crisis |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson is admitted to hospital for tests after testing positive for coronavirus ten days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52177125 |title=Coronavirus: PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*6 April\n**[[Debenhams]], one of the UK's largest and oldest department stores, goes into administration for the second time in a year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/apr/06/debenhams-appoint-administrators-second-time-in-year-coronavirus-lockdown|title=Debenhams to appoint administrators for second time in a year|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The death toll from COVID-19 in the UK exceeds 5,000. The total number of reported cases is nearly 52,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/06/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-spends-night-in-hospital?page=with:block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404#block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404|title=UK death toll rises to 5,373|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is taken into [[intensive care unit|intensive care]] after being admitted to hospital for coronavirus the day before. It is announced that [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] will deputise for him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*8 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Resolution Foundation]], using figures from the [[British Chambers of Commerce]], reports that more than nine million workers are expected to be [[Furlough|furloughed]] under the government's job retention scheme, with an estimated cost to the taxpayer of between \u00a330 and 40bn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52209790 |title=Coronavirus: More than 9 million expected to be furloughed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*9 April\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] says the UK is \"starting to see the impact\" of the restrictions but that it is \"too early\" to lift them, and urges people to stay indoors over the Easter weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52235492|title=Raab urges UK public not to ruin lockdown progress|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is moved out of intensive care, but remains in hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n*11 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes her first ever [[Easter]] message to the nation, in which she states \"coronavirus will not overcome us\" and that \"we need Easter as much as ever.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52255054 |title=Coronavirus: 'We need Easter as much as ever,' says the Queen |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*12 April\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is discharged from hospital after being treated for coronavirus and will continue his recovery at [[Chequers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52262012 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson discharged from hospital |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The number of people who died in hospital with coronavirus in the UK passes 10,000, after a daily rise of 737.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52264145 |title=Coronavirus: 'Sombre day' as UK deaths hit 10,000 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*16 April\n**A 99-year-old war veteran, [[Tom Moore (fundraiser)|Tom Moore]], raises over \u00a313&nbsp;million (subsequently raised over \u00a325&nbsp;million) for [[NHS Charities Together]] after walking more than 100 laps of his garden, with hundreds of thousands (subsequently over a million) of people donating to his [[JustGiving]] page.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52303859 |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore finishes NHS fundraiser as it tops \u00a313m |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] announces a three-week extension to the nationwide lockdown measures as the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in the UK surpasses 100,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52313715 |title=Coronavirus: UK lockdown extended for 'at least three weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*19 April &ndash; [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Michael Gove]], in a BBC interview with [[Andrew Marr]], concedes that the Prime Minister missed five [[Cabinet_Office_Briefing_Rooms|COBRA]] meetings in the early stages of the viral outbreak, and that the UK shipped [[personal protective equipment|protective equipment]] to China in February.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/19/michael-gove-fails-to-deny-pm-missed-five-coronavirus-cobra-meetings |title=Boris Johnson missed five coronavirus Cobra meetings, Gove says |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n*21 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Data from the [[Office for National Statistics (United Kingdom)|Office for National Statistics]] show the number of deaths in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England|England]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales|Wales]] has risen to its highest in 20 years. Figures show 18,500 deaths were recorded in the week up to 10 April, 8,000 more than usual for this time of year, with one in three linked to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52361519 |title=Coronavirus: Deaths at 20-year high but peak may be over |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=21 April 2020 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n*22 April \n**MPs take part in the first \"virtual\" [[Prime Minister's Questions]], via video conferencing service [[Zoom_Video_Communications|Zoom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/first-virtual-prime-ministers-questions-watch-live/ |title=The first \"Virtual\" Prime Minister's Questions: Watch live NOW |work=LBC |publisher=LBC |date=22 April 2020 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Chief Medical Officer for England|Chief Medical Officer]] [[Chris Whitty]] says it is likely the UK will have to live under some disruptive social distancing measures for at least the rest of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52389285 |title=Coronavirus: Social restrictions 'to remain for rest of year' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 April 2020 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n*23 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The first [[Clinical trial|human trial]] in Europe of a [[COVID-19 vaccine|coronavirus vaccine]] begins in [[Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52394485 |title=Coronavirus: First patients injected in UK vaccine trial |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 April 2020 |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n*24 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government launches a website for [[Key worker|key workers]] to apply for [[COVID-19 testing|coronavirus tests]] at drive-through centres and for home delivery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52418872 |title=Coronavrius test website reopens for bookings after 'significant demand' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 April 2020 |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n*25 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The number of people who died in hospital with coronavirus in the UK exceeds 20,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52424413 |title=Coronavrius: UK hospital deaths pass 20,000 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 April 2020 |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n*27 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Boris Johnson returns to work after three weeks of illness. In his first speech outside 10 Downing Street since recovering from coronavirus, he urges the public not to lose patience with the lockdown, warning that the UK is at the moment of \"maximum risk\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52439348 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson says this is moment of maximum risk |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 April 2020 |accessdate=27 April 2020}}</ref>\n*28 April \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A [[Moment of silence|minute's silence]] is held across the UK to commemorate the [[Key worker|key workers]] who have died with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52450138 |title=Coronavirus: UK holds minute's silence for key workers who died |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 April 2020 |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Figures from the [[Office for National Statistics (United Kingdom)|Office for National Statistics]] show a third of deaths in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England|England]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales|Wales]] from coronavirus are occurring in [[Nursing home care|care homes]], with 2,000 recorded in the week up to 17 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52455072 |title=Coronavirus: Care home deaths up as hospital cases fall |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 April 2020 |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Predicted and scheduled events ===\n* November \u2013 Glasgow is scheduled to host the 26th Conference of the Parties of the [[UN Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC) \u2013 a major UN climate change summit.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will |last=Hazell |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/2020-calendar-summits-elections-sporting-events-1353215 |title=2020 calendar: The major international summits, elections and sporting events of the year ahead |publisher=inews |date=1 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 December \u2013 The current expiration to the transition period, and deadline for negotiations on a future UK-EU relationship, after Brexit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-politics-50838994 |title=Brexit: What is the transition period? |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 December 2019 |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:Derek Acorah 2013 2013-11-21 01-05 (cropped).jpeg|upright|thumb|[[Derek Acorah]] in 2013]]\n[[File:Roger Scruton by Pete Helme.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Roger Scruton|Sir Roger Scruton]]]]\n[[File:Derek Fowlds Allan Warren.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Derek Fowlds]] in 1974]]\n[[File:Official portrait of Lord Maclennan of Rogart crop 2.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Robert Maclennan, Baron Maclennan of Rogart]] in 2018]]\n[[File:Terry Jones Monty Python O2 Arena (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|[[Terry Jones]] in 2014]]\n[[File:Nicholas Parsons 2007.png|upright|thumb|[[Nicholas Parsons]] in 2007]]\n*1 January\n**[[Chris Barker]], 39, English footballer ([[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50971215|title=Chris Barker: Former Cardiff City defender dies aged 39|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=2 January 2020|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Alexander Frater]], 82, travel writer and journalist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/commentisfree/2020/jan/05/obituary-alexander-frater-1937-2020|last=Chesshyre|first=Robert|title=Obituary: Alexander Frater 1937\u20132020|work=The Guardian|date=5 January 2020|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n*3 January\n**[[Derek Acorah]], 69, self-styled spiritual medium and television personality (''[[Most Haunted]]'', ''[[Derek Acorah's Ghost Towns]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50991908|title=Derek Acorah, TV medium, dies aged 69|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Christopher Beeny]], 78, actor (''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]'', ''[[In Loving Memory (TV series)|In Loving Memory]]'', ''[[Last of the Summer Wine]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51035015|title=Christopher Beeny: Upstairs, Downstairs actor dies at 78|work=BBC News|date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n*4 January\n**[[Guy Arnold]], 87, explorer and writer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/guy-arnold-obituary-hpbxnj9jl|title=Guy Arnold obituary|work=The Times|date=24 January 2020|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Jack Baldwin (chemist)|Sir Jack Baldwin]], 81, chemist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chemistryviews.org/details/ezine/11210979/Sir_Jack_Edward_Baldwin_1938__2020.html|title=Sir Jack Edward Baldwin (1938\u20132020)|publisher=Chemistry Views|date=10 January 2020|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n*5 January\n**[[James Barber (biochemist)|James Barber]], 79, biochemist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rutherford|first=Bill|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/194710/professor-james-barber-1940-2020/|title=Professor James Barber, 1940\u20132020|publisher=Imperial College London|date=13 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Colin Howson]], 74\u201375, philosopher.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/philosophy/blog/2020/01/08/colin-howson-1945-2020/|title=Colin Howson, 1945\u20132020|publisher=London School of Economics|date=8 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Sir Michael Stear]], 81, [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] air chief marshal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/238672/stear|title=Stear|publisher=Daily Telegraph: Announcements|date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n*6 January\n**[[Ray Byrom]], 85, English footballer ([[Accrington Stanley F.C. (1891)|Accrington Stanley]], [[Bradford (Park Avenue) A.F.C.|Bradford (Park Avenue)]]).<ref>{{cite news|last=Athey|first=Neil|url=https://www.thelancasterandmorecambecitizen.co.uk/news/18151114.ex-accrington-stanley-player-founder-garage-supplies-firm-ray-byrom-dies/|title=Ex-Accrington Stanley player and founder of garage supplies firm Ray Byrom dies|work=The Lancaster and Morecambe Citizen|date=10 January 2020|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Danny Masterton]], 65, Scottish footballer ([[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]], [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2020/01/06/6303/|title=Danny Masterton|publisher=Clyde F.C.|da