ing International, Inc.}}\n* Original Langster\n* [[3 Arts Entertainment]]\n* [[Universal Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Netflix]]\n| budget                   = \n| network                  = Netflix\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                = <!-- The nation in which the series first aired, if different from country parameter -->\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n| last_aired               = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| website                  = <!-- Remove or comment out this parameter line completely if URL exists on or is moved to Wikidata; use |website_title= to change the display title. -->\n| production_website       = <!-- use |production_website_title= to change the display title. -->\n}}\n'''''Never Have I Ever''''' is an American [[coming of age]] [[dramedy]] television series on [[Netflix]] starring [[Tamil Canadian]] actress [[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]] and created by [[Mindy Kaling]] and Lang Fisher. It premiered on April 27, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/tv-news-roundup-netflix-releases-trailer-mindy-kalings-never-have-i-ever-1234581321/|title=TV News Roundup: Netflix Releases 'Never Have I Ever' Trailer (Watch)|last=Shafer|first=Ellise|date=April 15, 2020|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/ramakrishnan-mindy-kaling-netflix-1.5265663|title='Be that change': Maitreyi Ramakrishnan on starring in Mindy Kaling's new comedy|date=August 30, 2019|work=CBC|access-date=April 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/watch-mindy-kaling-never-have-i-ever-trailer-netflix.html|title=Dear Gods, Meet Devi, a Young Mindy Kaling in Netflix's Never Have I Ever|last=Murphy|first=Chris|date=April 15, 2020|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/274c2a2a-7e6e-11ea-9bdd-1244d5f7c7c6/|title=Maitreyi Ramakrishnan talks TikTok drama, sex and embracing Tamil culture|last=Simonpillai|first=Radheyan|date=April 14, 2020|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/netflix-never-have-i-ever-messy-teenhood|title=\"Never Have I Ever\" Stars Promise Real, Messy Teenhood|last=Jaime|first=Angie|website=Teen Vogue|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/never-have-i-ever-netflix-trailer-release-date-mindy-kaling/|title='Never Have I Ever' Trailer Reveals Mindy Kaling's New Netflix Show|last=Lawrence|first=Gregory|date=April 15, 2020|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> The series has received positive reviews from critics.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{Cite web|title=Never Have I Ever: Season 1|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/never_have_i_ever/s01|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{Cite web|title=Never Have I Ever|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/never-have-i-ever|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAfter a horrible year, Devi Vishwakumar ([[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]]) wants to change her social status, but friends, family, and feelings would not make it easy on her. \n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* [[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]] as Devi Vishwakumar, a sophomore student who wants to improve her life.<ref name=\"Cast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/never-have-i-ever-cast|title=Meet the Cast of Netflix's \"Never Have I Ever,\" Your Next Fave Teen Comedy|last=Maloney|first=Alli|website=Teen Vogue|language=en|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Darren Barnet]] as Paxton Hall-Yoshida, a classmate of Devi's who is retaking the year.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ramona Young]] as Eleanor, one of Devi's best friends who enjoys acting.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* Lee Rodriguez as Fabiola, Devi's other best friend who enjoys science.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* Richa Moorjani as Kamala, Devi's cousin who is staying with her while she is completing her PhD.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* Jaren Lewison as Ben Gross, Devi's nemesis at school.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[John McEnroe]] as Himself, the narrator of the series.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=John McEnroe To Narrate Netflix\u2019s Kaling/Fisher Comedy Series \u2018Never Have I Ever\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/john-mcenroe-narrate-netflix-kaling-fisher-comedy-series-never-have-i-ever-1202731927/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |accessdate=April 23, 2020 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]] as Dr. Nalini Vishwakumar, Devi's mother.<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Niecy Nash]] as Dr. Jamie Ryan, Devi\u2019s therapist.<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Sendhil Ramamurthy]] as Mohan Venkatesan, Devi's dead father who appears in flashbacks.\n* Benjamin Norris as Trent Harrison, Paxton's friend.\n* Adam Shapiro as Mr. Shapiro, a history teacher.\n* Martin Martinez as Oliver Martinez, Eleanor's boyfriend.\n* Christina Kartchner as Eve, a girl who has a crush on Fabiola.\n* Jack Seavor McDonald as Eric Perkins, an unpopular student.\n* Dino Petrera as Jonah Sharpe, a boy who comes out as gay.\n* Eddie Liu as Steve, Kamala\u2019s secret boyfriend \n* Lily D. Moore as Rebecca, Paxton\u2019s adopted sister\n* Hanna Stein as Shira, Ben\u2019s girlfriend\n* [[Angela Kinsey]] as Vivian, Ben's mother.\n* [[Michael Badalucco]] as Howard, Ben's father.\n* Donna Pieroni as Patty, Ben's housekeeper.\n* [[Andy Samberg]] as Himself, the narrator for Ben Gross's thoughts\n\n==Episodes==\n=== Season 1 (2020) ===\n{{Episode table |total_width= |background=#DE14CD |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/04/27/never-have-i-ever-review-netflix-mindy-kaling/|title=Mindy Kaling's smart teen sex romp \"Never Have I Ever\" may be her best series yet|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=April 27, 2020}}</ref> |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Pilot\n |DirectedBy      = [[Tristram Shapeero]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Mindy Kaling]] & Lang Fisher\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = After her dad dies and she is in a wheelchair for her freshman year, Devi comes up with a plan to have a good sophomore year. She pleads with best friends Eleanor and Fabiola to get boyfriends, so that the group become cool. However, when she discovers that Eleanor has a boyfriend, she has a breakdown and asks classmate Paxton if he wants to have sex. Devi's cousin Kamala is told that her marriage is being arranged. \n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = ... had sex with Paxton Hall-Yoshida\n |DirectedBy      = Tristram Shapeero\n |WrittenBy       = Justin Noble\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Devi leaves orchestra practice early to go to Paxton's house, but leaves when she does not feel ready to have sex. Kamala meets with her secret boyfriend, and tells him that she cannot see him anymore due to her arranged marriage.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = ... gotten drunk with the popular kids\n |DirectedBy      = [[Linda Mendoza]]\n |WrittenBy       = Amina Munir\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = In history class, Devi is delighted when Paxton asks her to be in his group, but overhears him saying he asked her to get a good grade. Eleanor and Fabiola team up with Eve, who Fabiola has a crush on. Fabiola then breaks up with her boyfriend and realises she is gay. Devi invites herself to a party, and sees Paxton flirting with a girl. A drunk Devi sees a coyote at the party, and believing it has the spirit of her dad, she talks to it. It attacks her, and she is taken to the hospital. Paxton sees her in hospital, and affirms that they are just friends. Inspired by a ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' scene, Kamala reconciles with her boyfriend.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = ... felt super Indian\n |DirectedBy      = Linda Mendoza\n |WrittenBy       = Mindy Kaling\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = At a Hindu convention at the school, Devi's mother Nalini asks Devi to smooth talk Ron, who is on the college admission board. Ron asks Devi to use her dad's death and her paralysis as a story to get into college, but she refuses. At the convention, Kamala meets a woman who is shunned due to refusing her arranged marriage. She tells Kamala to go ahead with her marriage. \n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = ... started a nuclear war\n |DirectedBy      = [[Kabir Akhtar]]\n |WrittenBy       = Chris Schleicher & Akshara Sekar\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Fabiola gathers her family members to [[come out]], but avoids telling them. Paxton tells Eleanor that her mother served them in a restaurant, despite her being told that she is working on a cruise as an actress. Fabiola accompanies her to the restaurant, where they see her mother. Afterwards, she comes out to Eleanor, who supports her. Devi joins [[Model United Nations|Model UN]], and fuels the lie that she and Paxton are sleeping together. She and nemesis Ben join forces to get the members alcohol. The next day, Devi turns against him in UN, and gets the members to stand alongside her. Paxton then confronts her and asks why she would use him.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = ... been the loneliest boy in the world\n |DirectedBy      = Kabir Akhtar\n |WrittenBy       = Aaron Geary & Ben Steiner\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Ben returns home from Model UN to his mother leaving for a self realisation resort. Planning to see a game court-side with his girlfriend and father, both cancel on him, so he gives the tickets to his housekeeper. Feeling lonely, he meets with a friend from an online forum, who turns out to be a 50-year-old man. Ben sees Nalini about a pimple, and she invites him to a dinner with her and the Vishwakumars. Initially upset with Ben coming over, Devi is pleasantly surprised when he does not expose her behavior at Model UN.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = ... been a big, fat liar\n |DirectedBy      = Anu Valia\n |WrittenBy       = Erica Oyama\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Devi tries to make it up to Eleanor and Fabiola. She visits Eleanor's mother and tells her to talk to Eleanor. She comes to the school and watches Eleanor rehearse for the play, but leaves midway through to go back to broadway. Distraught, Eleanor quits acting. Fabiola asks Davi to support her, but when Paxton texts her, she goes to his house instead.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = ... pissed off everyone I know\n |DirectedBy      = Anu Valia\n |WrittenBy       = Chris Schleicher\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Eleanor and Fabiola decide to take a break from Devi, so she goes to see her therapist. She tells Devi that all the drama is coming from the grief over her dad, and Devi says that she wants a new therapist. Ben throws a party for his birthday, and after Devi finds Kamala with boyfriend Steve, she makes Kamala sneak her to the party. After Devi learns that a classmate ruined the punch, she sees Fabiola about to drink it. She goes to swipe the drink from her, but accidentally spills the bowl of punch over her. Fabiola argues with her in front of the crowd, and accidentally comes out. Eve, who overheard, arranges a date with her. After Devi falls in the pool, Paxton takes her home and kisses her.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = ... had to be on my best behavior\n |DirectedBy      = Tristram Shapeero\n |WrittenBy       = [[Matt Warburton]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Kamala's arranged husband meets with the family over lunch for the first time. Devi enters Kamala's room to place a present that she got only to find that Steve is in there, waiting to rescue Kamala from her arrainged marriage. At Devi's behest, Kamala talk with Steve to sort things out. Nalini walks in on them and reveals that she knew about the two as a couple. Paxton arrives to return Devi's dress from the party, and accidentally reveals that Devi secretly attended Ben's party and that she and Paxton kissed. Nalini, enraged, yells at Paxton for \"ruining\" Devi's life. Devi's uncle reveals that Nalini is planning on moving them both to India. Devi gets in a fight with Nalini, and refuses to move.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = ... said I'm sorry\n |DirectedBy      = Tristram Shapeero\n |WrittenBy       = Lang Fisher\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Paxton avoids Devi following with incident with Nalini. Devi moves in with Ben so that she cannot be moved to India. Nalini visits her on Mohan's birthday and asks her to spread her father's ashes with her, but she refuses. To convince Devi to spread the ashes with Nalini, Ben enlists the help of Fabiola and Eleanor, who reconcile their friendship. They encourage Devi to go, so Ben takes her to Malibu. Devi, Nalini and Kamala spread Mohan's ashes and she agrees to move back in with them. Returning to Ben's car, the pair kiss. Meanwhile, Paxton, at his sister's urging to reconcile with Devi, leaves her a message while waiting at her front door.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\n<!--AUDIENCE RECEPTION AND RATINGS: Do not include them! Wikipedia does not support user-generated content in its articles, and thus audience ratings cannot be included. Please refer to the talk page before proceeding to edit this section, and view the multiple discussions raised on the topic. No consensus has been formed to allow this article to differ from Wikipedia's guidelines and policies by including such content. Additions of audience ratings will be reverted.-->\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the series holds an approval rating of 100% based on 27 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9/10.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\"/> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 82 out of 100 based on 16 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Never Have I Ever}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n\n{{comedy-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American television series}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| italic_title             = \n| name                = Never Have I Ever\n| image                    = Never Have I Ever Title Card.png\n| image_upright            = \n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[Dramedy]]\n| creator                  = [[Mindy Kaling]]<br>Lang Fisher\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]]\n* [[Darren Barnet]]\n* [[Ramona Young]]\n* Lee Rodriguez \n* Richa Moorjani\n* Jaren Lewison\n* [[John McEnroe]]\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]]\n}}\n| narrated                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John McEnroe]]\n* [[Andy Samberg]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!--Only increment as a new season has been released, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes             = 10<!--Only increment as a new episodes haven been released, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mindy Kaling\n* Lang Fisher\n* [[Howard Klein (television producer)|Howard Klein]]\n* [[David Miner (television producer)|David Miner]]\n* [[Tristram Shapeero]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| location                 = <!-- Nation the series was primarily filmed in, if different from the nation of origin. -->\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = <!-- Film editors -->\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 22\u201330 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* {{nowrap|Kaling International, Inc.}}\n* Original Langster\n* [[3 Arts Entertainment]]\n* [[Universal Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Netflix]]\n| budget                   = \n| network                  = Netflix\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                = <!-- The nation in which the series first aired, if different from country parameter -->\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n| last_aired               = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| website                  = <!-- Remove or comment out this parameter line completely if URL exists on or is moved to Wikidata; use |website_title= to change the display title. -->\n| production_website       = <!-- use |production_website_title= to change the display title. -->\n}}\n'''''Never Have I Ever''''' is an American [[coming of age]] [[dramedy]] television series on [[Netflix]] starring [[Tamil Canadian]] actress [[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]] and created by [[Mindy Kaling]] and Lang Fisher. It premiered on April 27, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/tv-news-roundup-netflix-releases-trailer-mindy-kalings-never-have-i-ever-1234581321/|title=TV News Roundup: Netflix Releases 'Never Have I Ever' Trailer (Watch)|last=Shafer|first=Ellise|date=April 15, 2020|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/ramakrishnan-mindy-kaling-netflix-1.5265663|title='Be that change': Maitreyi Ramakrishnan on starring in Mindy Kaling's new comedy|date=August 30, 2019|work=CBC|access-date=April 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/watch-mindy-kaling-never-have-i-ever-trailer-netflix.html|title=Dear Gods, Meet Devi, a Young Mindy Kaling in Netflix's Never Have I Ever|last=Murphy|first=Chris|date=April 15, 2020|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/274c2a2a-7e6e-11ea-9bdd-1244d5f7c7c6/|title=Maitreyi Ramakrishnan talks TikTok drama, sex and embracing Tamil culture|last=Simonpillai|first=Radheyan|date=April 14, 2020|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/netflix-never-have-i-ever-messy-teenhood|title=\"Never Have I Ever\" Stars Promise Real, Messy Teenhood|last=Jaime|first=Angie|website=Teen Vogue|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/never-have-i-ever-netflix-trailer-release-date-mindy-kaling/|title='Never Have I Ever' Trailer Reveals Mindy Kaling's New Netflix Show|last=Lawrence|first=Gregory|date=April 15, 2020|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> The series has received positive reviews from critics.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{Cite web|title=Never Have I Ever: Season 1|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/never_have_i_ever/s01|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{Cite web|title=Never Have I Ever|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/never-have-i-ever|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAfter a horrible year, Devi Vishwakumar ([[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]]) wants to change her social status, but friends, family, and feelings would not make it easy on her. \n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* [[Maitreyi Ramakrishnan]] as Devi Vishwakumar, a sophomore student who wants to improve her life.<ref name=\"Cast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/never-have-i-ever-cast|title=Meet the Cast of Netflix's \"Never Have I Ever,\" Your Next Fave Teen Comedy|last=Maloney|first=Alli|website=Teen Vogue|language=en|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Darren Barnet]] as Paxton Hall-Yoshida, a classmate of Devi's who is retaking the year.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ramona Young]] as Eleanor, one of Devi's best friends who enjoys acting.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* Lee Rodriguez as Fabiola, Devi's other best friend who enjoys science.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* Richa Moorjani as Kamala, Devi's cousin who is staying with her while she is completing her PhD.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* Jaren Lewison as Ben Gross, Devi's nemesis at school.<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[John McEnroe]] as Himself, the narrator of the series.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=John McEnroe To Narrate Netflix\u2019s Kaling/Fisher Comedy Series \u2018Never Have I Ever\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/john-mcenroe-narrate-netflix-kaling-fisher-comedy-series-never-have-i-ever-1202731927/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |accessdate=April 23, 2020 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]] as Dr. Nalini Vishwakumar, Devi's mother.<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Niecy Nash]] as Dr. Jamie Ryan, Devi\u2019s therapist.<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Sendhil Ramamurthy]] as Mohan Venkatesan, Devi's dead father who appears in flashbacks.\n* Benjamin Norris as Trent Harrison, Paxton's friend.\n* Adam Shapiro as Mr. Shapiro, a history teacher.\n* Martin Martinez as Oliver Martinez, Eleanor's boyfriend.\n* Christina Kartchner as Eve, a girl who has a crush on Fabiola.\n* Jack Seavor McDonald as Eric Perkins, an unpopular student.\n* Dino Petrera as Jonah Sharpe, a boy who comes out as gay.\n* Eddie Liu as Steve, Kamala\u2019s secret boyfriend \n* Lily D. Moore as Rebecca, Paxton\u2019s adopted sister\n* Hanna Stein as Shira, Ben\u2019s girlfriend\n* [[Angela Kinsey]] as Vivian, Ben's mother.\n* [[Michael Badalucco]] as Howard, Ben's father.\n* Donna Pieroni as Patty, Ben's housekeeper.\n* [[Andy Samberg]] as Himself, the narrator for Ben Gross's thoughts\n\n==Episodes==\n=== Season 1 (2020) ===\n{{Episode table |total_width= |background=#DE14CD |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/04/27/never-have-i-ever-review-netflix-mindy-kaling/|title=Mindy Kaling's smart teen sex romp \"Never Have I Ever\" may be her best series yet|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=April 27, 2020}}</ref> |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Pilot\n |DirectedBy      = [[Tristram Shapeero]]\n |WrittenBy       = [[Mindy Kaling]] & Lang Fisher\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = After her dad dies and she is in a wheelchair for her freshman year, Devi comes up with a plan to have a good sophomore year. She pleads with best friends Eleanor and Fabiola to get boyfriends, so that the group become cool. However, when she discovers that Eleanor has a boyfriend, she has a breakdown and asks classmate Paxton if he wants to have sex. Devi's cousin Kamala is told that her marriage is being arranged. \n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = ... had sex with Paxton Hall-Yoshida\n |DirectedBy      = Tristram Shapeero\n |WrittenBy       = Justin Noble\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Devi leaves orchestra practice early to go to Paxton's house, but leaves when she does not feel ready to have sex. Kamala meets with her secret boyfriend, and tells him that she cannot see him anymore due to her arranged marriage.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = ... gotten drunk with the popular kids\n |DirectedBy      = [[Linda Mendoza]]\n |WrittenBy       = Amina Munir\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = In history class, Devi is delighted when Paxton asks her to be in his group, but overhears him saying he asked her to get a good grade. Eleanor and Fabiola team up with Eve, who Fabiola has a crush on. Fabiola then breaks up with her boyfriend and realises she is gay. Devi invites herself to a party, and sees Paxton flirting with a girl. A drunk Devi sees a coyote at the party, and believing it has the spirit of her dad, she talks to it. It attacks her, and she is taken to the hospital. Paxton sees her in hospital, and affirms that they are just friends. Inspired by a ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' scene, Kamala reconciles with her boyfriend.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = ... felt super Indian\n |DirectedBy      = Linda Mendoza\n |WrittenBy       = Mindy Kaling\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = At a Hindu convention at the school, Devi's mother Nalini asks Devi to smooth talk Ron, who is on the college admission board. Ron asks Devi to use her dad's death and her paralysis as a story to get into college, but she refuses. At the convention, Kamala meets a woman who is shunned due to refusing her arranged marriage. She tells Kamala to go ahead with her marriage. \n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = ... started a nuclear war\n |DirectedBy      = [[Kabir Akhtar]]\n |WrittenBy       = Chris Schleicher & Akshara Sekar\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Fabiola gathers her family members to [[come out]], but avoids telling them. Paxton tells Eleanor that her mother served them in a restaurant, despite her being told that she is working on a cruise as an actress. Fabiola accompanies her to the restaurant, where they see her mother. Afterwards, she comes out to Eleanor, who supports her. Devi joins [[Model United Nations|Model UN]], and fuels the lie that her and Paxton are sleeping together. Her and nemesis Ben join forces to get the members alcohol. The next day, Devi turns against him in UN, and gets the members to stand alongside her. Paxton then confronts her and asks why she would use him.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = ... been the loneliest boy in the world\n |DirectedBy      = Kabir Akhtar\n |WrittenBy       = Aaron Geary & Ben Steiner\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Ben returns home from Model UN to his mother leaving for a self realisation resort. Planning to see a game court-side with his girlfriend and father, both cancel on him, so he gives the tickets to his housekeeper. Feeling lonely, he meets with a friend from an online forum, who turns out to be a 50-year-old man. Ben sees Nalini about a pimple, and she invites him to a dinner with her and the Vishwakumars. Initially upset with Ben coming over, Devi is pleasantly surprised when he does not expose her behavior at Model UN.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = ... been a big, fat liar\n |DirectedBy      = Anu Valia\n |WrittenBy       = Erica Oyama\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Devi tries to make it up to Eleanor and Fabiola. She visits Eleanor's mother and tells her to talk to Eleanor. She comes to the school and watches Eleanor rehearse for the play, but leaves midway through to go back to broadway. Distraught, Eleanor quits acting. Fabiola asks Davi to support her, but when Paxton texts her, she goes to his house instead.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = ... pissed off everyone I know\n |DirectedBy      = Anu Valia\n |WrittenBy       = Chris Schleicher\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Eleanor and Fabiola decide to take a break from Devi, so she goes to see her therapist. She tells Devi that all the drama is coming from the grief over her dad, and Devi says that she wants a new therapist. Ben throws a party for his birthday, and after Devi finds Kamala with boyfriend Steve, she makes Kamala sneak her to the party. After Devi learns that a classmate ruined the punch, she sees Fabiola about to drink it. She goes to swipe the drink from her, but accidentally spills the bowl of punch over her. Fabiola argues with her in front of the crowd, and accidentally comes out. Eve, who overheard, arranges a date with her. After Devi falls in the pool, Paxton takes her home and kisses her.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = ... had to be on my best behavior\n |DirectedBy      = Tristram Shapeero\n |WrittenBy       = [[Matt Warburton]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Kamala's arranged husband meets with the family over lunch for the first time. Devi enters Kamala's room to place a present that she got only to find that Steve is in there, waiting to rescue Kamala from her arrainged marriage. At Devi's behest, Kamala talk with Steve to sort things out. Nalini walks in on them and reveals that she knew about the two as a couple. Paxton arrives to return Devi's dress from the party, and accidentally reveals that Devi secretly attended Ben's party and that she and Paxton kissed. Nalini, enraged, yells at Paxton for \"ruining\" Devi's life. Devi's uncle reveals that Nalini is planning on moving them both to India. Devi gets in a fight with Nalini, and refuses to move.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = ... said I'm sorry\n |DirectedBy      = Tristram Shapeero\n |WrittenBy       = Lang Fisher\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary    = Paxton avoids Devi following with incident with Nalini. Devi moves in with Ben so that she cannot be moved to India. Nalini visits her on Mohan's birthday and asks her to spread her father's ashes with her, but she refuses. To convince Devi to spread the ashes with Nalini, Ben enlists the help of Fabiola and Eleanor, who reconcile their friendship. They encourage Devi to go, so Ben takes her to Malibu. Devi, Nalini and Kamala spread Mohan's ashes and she agrees to move back in with them. Returning to Ben's car, the pair kiss. Meanwhile, Paxton, at his sister's urging to reconcile with Devi, leaves her a message while waiting at her front door.\n |LineColor       = DE14CD\n}}\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\n<!--AUDIENCE RECEPTION AND RATINGS: Do not include them! Wikipedia does not support user-generated content in its articles, and thus audience ratings cannot be included. Please refer to the talk page before proceeding to edit this section, and view the multiple discussions raised on the topic. No consensus has been formed to allow this article to differ from Wikipedia's guidelines and policies by including such content. Additions of audience ratings will be reverted.-->\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the series holds an approval rating of 100% based on 27 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9/10.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\"/> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 82 out of 100 based on 16 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Never Have I Ever}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n\n{{comedy-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 1 (2020):2x her\u2192she", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Never_Have_I_Ever_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Belleview Inn", "text_new": "{{infobox building|name=Belleview Inn\n|location=25 Belleview Blvd, [[Belleair, Florida]]\n|coordinates={{coord|27.943686|-82.809746|source:Doncram|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type=Florida\n|completion_date=1897\n}}\nThe '''Belleview Inn''', in [[Belleair, Florida]], dates from 1897. \n\n[[Henry Plant]], \"a railroad and steamship entrepreneur in 19th century who realized that his passengers would need somewhere to stay. Plant built a grand, Queen Anne-style Victorian hotel...\"\n\nIt was built of heart pine wood from Plant's Georgia property, and overlooks [[Clearwater Bay]].<ref name=hha-history>{{cite web|url=https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/belleview-inn/history.php |title=Belleview Inn: History |publisher=[[Historic Hotels of America]] |date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is a member of [[Historic Hotels of America]].<ref name=hha>{{cite web|url=https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/belleview-inn/ |title=Belleview Inn |publisher=[[Historic Hotels of America]] |date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Florida]]\n\n{{Florida-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{infobox building|name=Belleview Inn\n|location=25 Belleview Blvd, [[Belleair, Florida]]\n|coordinates={{coord|27.943686|-82.809746|source:Doncram|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type=Florida\n|completion_date=1897\n}}\nThe '''Belleview Inn''', in [[Belleair, Florida]], dates from 1897. \n\n[[Henry Plant]], \"a railroad and steamship entrepreneur in 19th century who realized that his passengers would need somewhere to stay. Plant built a grand, Queen Anne-style Victorian hotel...\"\n\nIt was built of heart pine wood from Plant's Georgia property, and overlooks [[Clearwater Bay]].<ref name=hha-history>{{cite web|url=https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/belleview-inn/history.php |title=Belleview Inn: History |publisher=[[Historic Hotels of America]] |date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is a member of [[Historic Hotels of America]].<ref name=hha>{{cite web|url=https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/belleview-inn/ |title=Belleview Inn |publisher=[[Historic Hotels of America]] |date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Florida]]\n[[Category:Belleair, Florida]]\n\n{{Florida-stub}}\n", "name_user": "TheImaCow", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:Belleair, FloridausingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belleview_Inn"}
{"title_page": "Ben Lee", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Ben Lee\n| image           = Ben Lee australia day live.jpg\n| caption         = Lee at the 2008 [[Australia Day Live Concert]] in Canberra\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Benjamin Michael Lee\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|9|11}}\n| birth_place     = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| instrument      = Vocals, guitar, bass, piano\n| genre           = [[Indie pop]]\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* Ten Fingers/Inertia\n* [[ABC Music (record label)|ABC Music]]\n* [[Dangerbird Records|Dangerbird]]\n* [[Modular Recordings|Modular]]\n* New West Records\n* [[Lojinx]]\n* [[Dew Process]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[Noise Addict]], [[The Bens]], [[Gerling]], [[Jessica Chapnik]], [[Radnor and Lee]], [[TwoSet Violin|Ling Ling]]\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.ben-lee.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Michael Lee''' (born 11 September 1978) is an [[Australia]]n musician and actor. Lee began his career as a musician at the age of 14 with the Sydney band [[Noise Addict]], but focused on his solo career when the band broke up in 1995. He appeared as the protagonist in the Australian film ''[[The Rage in Placid Lake]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|magazine=Filmink|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/australian-singers-turned-actors/|title=Australian Singers Turned Actors|date=July 14, 2019}}</ref>  He has released eleven solo studio albums.\n\n==Career==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=July 2017}}\n\n===Noise Addict===\nLee's musical career began in 1993 with the band [[Noise Addict]], who were signed to [[Steve Pavlovic]]'s independent label Fellaheen Records, on the strength of a self-produced and distributed four-track demo recorded in Lee's bedroom. Pavlovic's connections brought the band to the attention of [[Sonic Youth]]'s [[Thurston Moore]] and [[Beastie Boys]]' [[Mike D (musician)|Mike D]], both of whom released the band's material in the US. The group put out several releases on the Beasties' [[Grand Royal Records]].\n\nThese including the acoustic ''Young and Jaded'' EP in 1994, which contained Lee's [[Evan Dando]] tribute, \"I Wish I Was Him\". In 1995, Grand Royal released the band's only full-length album, the [[Brad Wood]]-produced ''Meet the Real You''. Noise Addict made a music video for the song \"16\", toured with [[Sebadoh]], but then broke up. Lee was also briefly a member of the alternative act [[Gerling]]. In 2009 Lee recorded a new Noise Addict album, ''It Was Never About the Audience'', with a new lineup; [[Lou Barlow]] and [[Lara Meyerratken]].\n\n===Solo career===\nLee's solo career started at the age of 16, while he was still in Noise Addict. He began recording his first solo album, ''[[Grandpaw Would]]'', in both Sydney and [[Chicago]] with producer [[Brad Wood]]. This was followed by the 1997 album, ''[[Something to Remember Me By]]'', also produced by Wood. An alternate version of his song \"Burn to Shine\", produced by [[T-Bone Burnett]], played over the end credits of the film ''[[Best Men]]''. Lee was then featured on the ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'' soundtrack, with the song \"How to Survive a Broken Heart\". 1998's ''[[Breathing Tornados]]'', released on Pavlovic's new label [[Modular Recordings|Modular]], marked a new direction for Lee as he introduced synthesisers and increased instrumentation into his sound.poo\n\nThe album was a success in Australia, earning Lee [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA Award]] nominations for Best Male Artist and Album of the Year. The album's first single, \"[[Cigarettes Will Kill You]]\", was also nominated for Single of the Year and finished second in that year's [[Triple J Hottest 100, 1998|Triple J Hottest 100]]. In 2001, Lee contributed a track (\"Sweet Is the Night\") to a Jeff Lynne tribute album ''[[Lynne Me Your Ears]]''.\n\nLee's fourth album, ''[[Hey You. Yes You.|hey you. yes you.]]'', was released in 2002. The first single from the album, \"Something Borrowed, Something Blue\", reached number 67 on the [[ARIA Charts]] and number 22 on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2002|2002's Triple J Hottest 100]]. The second single, \"Running with Scissors\", peaked at number 82 on the ARIA charts. In 2003, he also contributed several songs to the [[Evan Dando]] solo album ''Baby I'm Bored''.\n\nIn late 2004, Lee left Steve Pavlovic's [[Modular Recordings]] and started his own record label, Ten Fingers. The first release on the label was the single, \"[[Gamble Everything for Love]]\", followed by the album, ''[[Awake Is the New Sleep]]'' in February 2005, which went double platinum in Australia. A defining release in his career, the album showcased a much brighter, positive side of Lee's personality, in contrast to his previous darker musings. ''Awake Is the New Sleep'' received several nominations for the 2005 [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) awards, and Lee won Best Male Artist, Best Independent Release, and Single of the Year for \"[[Catch My Disease]]\", which Lee wrote with Mcgowan Southworth. \"Catch My Disease\" also went to No. 2 on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2005|2005 Triple J Hottest 100]].\n\nIn addition, the song was featured on the soundtracks to the 2005 films ''[[Just Friends]]'' and ''[[Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo]]'', as well as the soundtracks to the television series, ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', ''[[Hidden Palms]]'' and ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''. In 2006 it was used in a television commercial for [[Dell]] Computers. On 26 March 2006, Lee performed \"We're All in This Together\" from ''[[Awake Is the New Sleep]]'' at the closing ceremony of the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]]. The single for \"We're All in This Together\" was released on 8 April 2006. The CD includes cover versions of the song by Pony Up, Holidays on Ice and Gelbison. \"We're All in This Together\" is being used in commercials for Kohl's (2008), Coca-Cola ([[Remix]]ed Australian Summer Series Ads in 2007), the South Australian Government (2006), the Salvation Army Red Shield Appeal (2007) and [[Telus]] Mobility's \"My Faves\" (2007).\n\nLee released his sixth album, ''[[Ripe (Ben Lee album)|Ripe]]'', on 18 September 2007 with [[Benji Madden]] and [[Mandy Moore]] making appearances. Mandy Moore sung a light-hearted, '50s style duet with Lee called \"Birds and Bees\". \"Mandy was very sweet and did her best Olivia Newton-John for me. I'm really psyched about this recording,\" Lee says. Madden helped out with some backing vocals, along with US band [[Rooney (band)|Rooney]] and Sara Watkins from the band [[Nickel Creek]]. \"American Television\" from the album was used in a VH1 advertisement for ''[[Flavor of Love 3]]'' and the song \"Ripe\" appeared in an episode of ''One Tree Hill'' (Season 5, episode 2).\n\nIn 2007, Lee performed a cover of [[Crosby, Stills & Nash]]'s \"[[Our House (Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young song)|Our House]]\" for Landmarks on The DL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinner.com/2007/10/29/the-dl-rock-landmarks-featuring-ben-lee|title=AOL Radio Stations &#124; Free Internet Radio|website=Spinner.com|accessdate=5 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212214954/http://www.spinner.com/2007/10/29/the-dl-rock-landmarks-featuring-ben-lee|archivedate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, Lee released his seventh studio album, ''[[The Rebirth of Venus]]'', which received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-rebirth-of-venus|title=Reviews for The Rebirth of Venus by Ben Lee|website=Metacritic.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> It featured guest performances from the likes of [[Missy Higgins]] and [[Patience Hodgson]], and peaked at No.21 on the [[ARIA Charts]].<ref name=\"AUS\"/>\n\nLee's eighth studio album, ''[[Deeper into Dream]]'', was released on 11 October 2011. It was Lee's first attempt at a concept album, basing the entire 12 tracks around the [[dream]] state. Despite not charting,<ref name=\"AUS\"/> it was received fairly favourably by critics.\n\nIn April 2013, Lee released his ninth and arguably his most experimental studio album entitled ''[[Ayahuasca: Welcome to the Work]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/benlee/updates/20514|title=Ben Lee|website=Pledgemusic.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> with collaboration from [[Jessica Chapnik]]. The album is based upon his personal experience with the psychoactive South American drug known as [[Ayahuasca]]. Lee featured as the mentor for [[Joel Madden]]'s team on the 2013 season of ''[[The Voice (Australian TV series)|The Voice Australia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Annabel Ross|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/the-voice-is-my-rebirth-20130404-2h7qy.html|title=The Voice &#124; Ben Lee|website=Theage.com.au|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Lee released his 10th solo album, ''[[Love Is the Great Rebellion]]'', his first on a major label, Warner Bros. Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/av/2015/05/album-premiere-listen-to-ben-lees-love-is-the-grea.html|title=Album Premiere: Listen to Ben Lee's Love Is the Great Rebellion|website=Pastemagazine.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> According to [http://Geoff%20Wood%20at%20ABChttp://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/rhythmdivine/yoga-music-goes-mainstream/6556536 Geoff Wood at ABC]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Lee invented the term \"[[Electroyoga]]\" to describe a new form of music dedicated to the practice of yoga. Lee has since followed up this release with an acoustically-oriented album, entitled ''Freedom, Love and Recuperation of the Human Mind'', in 2016; as well as a [[children's music|children's album]], called ''Ben Lee Sings Songs About [[Islam]] for the Whole Family'', in 2017. November 2017 also saw the release of [[Radnor and Lee]], a collaborative album Lee made with former ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'' star [[Josh Radnor]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLee was born in Sydney and was raised in a [[Australian Jews|Jewish]] household, but did not consider himself religious as a child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonathan-talat-phillips/ben-lee-ayahuasca_b_3487688.html|title=Pop Singer Ben Lee Comes Out of the 'Ayahuasca Closet' [INTERVIEW]|work=The Huffington Post|date=24 June 2013}}</ref> Lee was educated at [[Moriah College]], an [[Independent school|independent]], [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox Jewish]], [[co-education]]al, [[Jewish day school|day school]], located in Sydney's eastern suburbs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/11/08/1036308480999.html|title=The ballad of Ben Lee|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=9 November 2002|author=Molitorisz, Sacha|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nLee dated [[Claire Danes]] for several years but their relationship ended in 2003, and he later married actress [[Ione Skye]] on 28 December 2008, in a [[Hindu]] wedding ceremony in [[India]]. They have one child.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|title=The many layers of Mr. Lee|date=2 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20251556,00.html|title=A Wedding in India for Actress Ione Skye|work=People.com|date=11 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Lee was nominated as [[PETA]]'s World's Sexiest Vegetarian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta2.com/outthere/o-sexyveg08_winners.asp|title=The 2008 World's Sexiest Vegetarians Are...|work=Out There |publisher=[[PETA]]|accessdate=25 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ppKBfYha?url=http://www.peta2.com/outthere/o-sexyveg08_winners.asp|archivedate=18 May 2010}}</ref> However, according to one source, Lee admitted he eats fish, indicating a [[pescatarian]] diet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vegetarianstar.com/2008/09/22/should-ben-lee-be-de-throned|title=Vegetarian StarShould Ben Lee Be De-Throned?|website=Vegetarianstar.com|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! colspan=\"1\"| Peak\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Certification\n|-\n! style=\"font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\">Peaks in Australia:\n* Top 50 peaks: {{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ben+Lee|title=australian-charts.com \u2013 Discography Ben Lee|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=29 July 2016}}\n* Top 100 peaks to December 2010: {{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}\n* \"Nothing Much Happens\": {{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/q1abuq2.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received 24 May 2016|publisher=Imgur.com|accessdate=26 November 2016}}\n* ''Love Is the Great Rebellion'': {{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-florence-the-machine-debuts-at-no-1-20150606|title=ARIA Albums: Florence + The Machine Debuts at No 1|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=6 June 2015|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Grandpaw Would]]''\n|\n* Released: 22 June 1995\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Something to Remember Me By]]''\n|\n* Released: 20 May 1997\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Breathing Tornados]]''\n|\n* Released: 16 November 1998\n| 13\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Hey You. Yes You.|hey you. yes you.]]''\n|\n* Released: 15 November 2002\n| 45\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Awake Is the New Sleep]]''\n|\n* Released: 22 February 2005\n| 5\n|\n* ARIA: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref>{{cite certification|region=Australia|type=album|relyear=2005|certyear=2005|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Ben Lee Sings [[Against Me!]]'s'' [[New Wave (Against Me! album)|New Wave]]\n|\n* Released: 19 August 2007\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ripe (Ben Lee album)|Ripe]]''\n|\n* Released: 18 September 2007\n| 11\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[The Rebirth of Venus]]''\n|\n* Released: 6 February 2009\n| 21\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Deeper into Dream]]''\n|\n* Released: 11 October 2011\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ayahuasca: Welcome to the Work]]''\n|\n* Released: 22 April 2013\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''A mixtape from Ben Lee''\n|\n* Released: 24 February 2015\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Love Is the Great Rebellion]]''\n|\n* Released: 29 May 2015\n| 71\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Freedom, Love and The Recuperation of the Human Mind''\n|\n* Released: 21 October 2016\n|\u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Ben Lee Sings Songs about Islam for the Whole Family''\n|\n* Released: 3 March 2017\n|\u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Radnor & Lee'' <small>(with [[Josh Radnor]])</small>\n|\n* Released: 10 November 2017\n|\u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[B Is for Beer|B Is for Beer: The Musical]]'' <small>(with [[Tom Robbins]])</small>\n|\n* Released: 12 October 2018\n|\u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Quarter Century Classix''\n|\n* Released: 22 November 2019\n|\u2014\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n*''Pop Queen'' (1994)\n*''Away with the Pixies'' (1995)\n*''The Dirty Little Secret EP'' (2002)\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/3825/