egory:Jewish Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:Lojinx artists]]\n[[Category:Dew Process artists]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Sydney]]\n[[Category:New West Records artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian male actors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Moriah College]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:The Bens members]]\n[[Category:Gerling members]]\n[[Category:Noise Addict members]]\n[[Category:Radnor and Lee members]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Ben Lee\n| image           = Ben Lee australia day live.jpg\n| caption         = Lee at the 2008 [[Australia Day Live Concert]] in Canberra\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Benjamin Michael Lee\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|9|11}}\n| birth_place     = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| instrument      = Vocals, guitar, bass, piano\n| genre           = [[Indie pop]]\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* Ten Fingers/Inertia\n* [[ABC Music (record label)|ABC Music]]\n* [[Dangerbird Records|Dangerbird]]\n* [[Modular Recordings|Modular]]\n* New West Records\n* [[Lojinx]]\n* [[Dew Process]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[Noise Addict]], [[The Bens]], [[Gerling]], [[Jessica Chapnik]], [[Radnor and Lee]], [[TwoSet Violin|Ling Ling]]\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.ben-lee.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Michael Lee''' (born 11 September 1978) is an [[Australia]]n musician and actor. Lee began his career as a musician at the age of 14 with the Sydney band [[Noise Addict]], but focused on his solo career when the band broke up in 1995. He appeared as the protagonist in the Australian film ''[[The Rage in Placid Lake]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|magazine=Filmink|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/australian-singers-turned-actors/|title=Australian Singers Turned Actors|date=July 14, 2019}}</ref>  He has released eleven solo studio albums.\n\n==Career==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=July 2017}}\n\n===Noise Addict===\nLee's musical career began in 1993 with the band [[Noise Addict]], who were signed to [[Steve Pavlovic]]'s independent label Fellaheen Records, on the strength of a self-produced and distributed four-track demo recorded in Lee's bedroom. Pavlovic's connections brought the band to the attention of [[Sonic Youth]]'s [[Thurston Moore]] and [[Beastie Boys]]' [[Mike D (musician)|Mike D]], both of whom released the band's material in the US. The group put out several releases on the Beasties' [[Grand Royal Records]].\n\nThese including the acoustic ''Young and Jaded'' EP in 1994, which contained Lee's [[Evan Dando]] tribute, \"I Wish I Was Him\". In 1995, Grand Royal released the band's only full-length album, the [[Brad Wood]]-produced ''Meet the Real You''. Noise Addict made a music video for the song \"16\", toured with [[Sebadoh]], but then broke up. Lee was also briefly a member of the alternative act [[Gerling]]. In 2009 Lee recorded a new Noise Addict album, ''It Was Never About the Audience'', with a new lineup; [[Lou Barlow]] and [[Lara Meyerratken]].\n\n===Solo career===\nLee's solo career started at the age of 16, while he was still in Noise Addict. He began recording his first solo album, ''[[Grandpaw Would]]'', in both Sydney and [[Chicago]] with producer [[Brad Wood]]. This was followed by the 1997 album, ''[[Something to Remember Me By]]'', also produced by Wood. An alternate version of his song \"Burn to Shine\", produced by [[T-Bone Burnett]], played over the end credits of the film ''[[Best Men]]''. Lee was then featured on the ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'' soundtrack, with the song \"How to Survive a Broken Heart\". 1998's ''[[Breathing Tornados]]'', released on Pavlovic's new label [[Modular Recordings|Modular]], marked a new direction for Lee as he introduced synthesisers and increased instrumentation into his sound.\n\nThe album was a success in Australia, earning Lee [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA Award]] nominations for Best Male Artist and Album of the Year. The album's first single, \"[[Cigarettes Will Kill You]]\", was also nominated for Single of the Year and finished second in that year's [[Triple J Hottest 100, 1998|Triple J Hottest 100]]. In 2001, Lee contributed a track (\"Sweet Is the Night\") to a Jeff Lynne tribute album ''[[Lynne Me Your Ears]]''.\n\nLee's fourth album, ''[[Hey You. Yes You.|hey you. yes you.]]'', was released in 2002. The first single from the album, \"Something Borrowed, Something Blue\", reached number 67 on the [[ARIA Charts]] and number 22 on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2002|2002's Triple J Hottest 100]]. The second single, \"Running with Scissors\", peaked at number 82 on the ARIA charts. In 2003, he also contributed several songs to the [[Evan Dando]] solo album ''Baby I'm Bored''.\n\nIn late 2004, Lee left Steve Pavlovic's [[Modular Recordings]] and started his own record label, Ten Fingers. The first release on the label was the single, \"[[Gamble Everything for Love]]\", followed by the album, ''[[Awake Is the New Sleep]]'' in February 2005, which went double platinum in Australia. A defining release in his career, the album showcased a much brighter, positive side of Lee's personality, in contrast to his previous darker musings. ''Awake Is the New Sleep'' received several nominations for the 2005 [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) awards, and Lee won Best Male Artist, Best Independent Release, and Single of the Year for \"[[Catch My Disease]]\", which Lee wrote with Mcgowan Southworth. \"Catch My Disease\" also went to No. 2 on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2005|2005 Triple J Hottest 100]].\n\nIn addition, the song was featured on the soundtracks to the 2005 films ''[[Just Friends]]'' and ''[[Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo]]'', as well as the soundtracks to the television series, ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', ''[[Hidden Palms]]'' and ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''. In 2006 it was used in a television commercial for [[Dell]] Computers. On 26 March 2006, Lee performed \"We're All in This Together\" from ''[[Awake Is the New Sleep]]'' at the closing ceremony of the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]]. The single for \"We're All in This Together\" was released on 8 April 2006. The CD includes cover versions of the song by Pony Up, Holidays on Ice and Gelbison. \"We're All in This Together\" is being used in commercials for Kohl's (2008), Coca-Cola ([[Remix]]ed Australian Summer Series Ads in 2007), the South Australian Government (2006), the Salvation Army Red Shield Appeal (2007) and [[Telus]] Mobility's \"My Faves\" (2007).\n\nLee released his sixth album, ''[[Ripe (Ben Lee album)|Ripe]]'', on 18 September 2007 with [[Benji Madden]] and [[Mandy Moore]] making appearances. Mandy Moore sung a light-hearted, '50s style duet with Lee called \"Birds and Bees\". \"Mandy was very sweet and did her best Olivia Newton-John for me. I'm really psyched about this recording,\" Lee says. Madden helped out with some backing vocals, along with US band [[Rooney (band)|Rooney]] and Sara Watkins from the band [[Nickel Creek]]. \"American Television\" from the album was used in a VH1 advertisement for ''[[Flavor of Love 3]]'' and the song \"Ripe\" appeared in an episode of ''One Tree Hill'' (Season 5, episode 2).\n\nIn 2007, Lee performed a cover of [[Crosby, Stills & Nash]]'s \"[[Our House (Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young song)|Our House]]\" for Landmarks on The DL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinner.com/2007/10/29/the-dl-rock-landmarks-featuring-ben-lee|title=AOL Radio Stations &#124; Free Internet Radio|website=Spinner.com|accessdate=5 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212214954/http://www.spinner.com/2007/10/29/the-dl-rock-landmarks-featuring-ben-lee|archivedate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, Lee released his seventh studio album, ''[[The Rebirth of Venus]]'', which received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-rebirth-of-venus|title=Reviews for The Rebirth of Venus by Ben Lee|website=Metacritic.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> It featured guest performances from the likes of [[Missy Higgins]] and [[Patience Hodgson]], and peaked at No.21 on the [[ARIA Charts]].<ref name=\"AUS\"/>\n\nLee's eighth studio album, ''[[Deeper into Dream]]'', was released on 11 October 2011. It was Lee's first attempt at a concept album, basing the entire 12 tracks around the [[dream]] state. Despite not charting,<ref name=\"AUS\"/> it was received fairly favourably by critics.\n\nIn April 2013, Lee released his ninth and arguably his most experimental studio album entitled ''[[Ayahuasca: Welcome to the Work]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/benlee/updates/20514|title=Ben Lee|website=Pledgemusic.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> with collaboration from [[Jessica Chapnik]]. The album is based upon his personal experience with the psychoactive South American drug known as [[Ayahuasca]]. Lee featured as the mentor for [[Joel Madden]]'s team on the 2013 season of ''[[The Voice (Australian TV series)|The Voice Australia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Annabel Ross|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/the-voice-is-my-rebirth-20130404-2h7qy.html|title=The Voice &#124; Ben Lee|website=Theage.com.au|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Lee released his 10th solo album, ''[[Love Is the Great Rebellion]]'', his first on a major label, Warner Bros. Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/av/2015/05/album-premiere-listen-to-ben-lees-love-is-the-grea.html|title=Album Premiere: Listen to Ben Lee's Love Is the Great Rebellion|website=Pastemagazine.com|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> According to [http://Geoff%20Wood%20at%20ABChttp://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/rhythmdivine/yoga-music-goes-mainstream/6556536 Geoff Wood at ABC]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Lee invented the term \"[[Electroyoga]]\" to describe a new form of music dedicated to the practice of yoga. Lee has since followed up this release with an acoustically-oriented album, entitled ''Freedom, Love and Recuperation of the Human Mind'', in 2016; as well as a [[children's music|children's album]], called ''Ben Lee Sings Songs About [[Islam]] for the Whole Family'', in 2017. November 2017 also saw the release of [[Radnor and Lee]], a collaborative album Lee made with former ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'' star [[Josh Radnor]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLee was born in Sydney and was raised in a [[Australian Jews|Jewish]] household, but did not consider himself religious as a child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonathan-talat-phillips/ben-lee-ayahuasca_b_3487688.html|title=Pop Singer Ben Lee Comes Out of the 'Ayahuasca Closet' [INTERVIEW]|work=The Huffington Post|date=24 June 2013}}</ref> Lee was educated at [[Moriah College]], an [[Independent school|independent]], [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox Jewish]], [[co-education]]al, [[Jewish day school|day school]], located in Sydney's eastern suburbs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/11/08/1036308480999.html|title=The ballad of Ben Lee|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=9 November 2002|author=Molitorisz, Sacha|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nLee dated [[Claire Danes]] for several years but their relationship ended in 2003, and he later married actress [[Ione Skye]] on 28 December 2008, in a [[Hindu]] wedding ceremony in [[India]]. They have one child.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|title=The many layers of Mr. Lee|date=2 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20251556,00.html|title=A Wedding in India for Actress Ione Skye|work=People.com|date=11 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Lee was nominated as [[PETA]]'s World's Sexiest Vegetarian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta2.com/outthere/o-sexyveg08_winners.asp|title=The 2008 World's Sexiest Vegetarians Are...|work=Out There |publisher=[[PETA]]|accessdate=25 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ppKBfYha?url=http://www.peta2.com/outthere/o-sexyveg08_winners.asp|archivedate=18 May 2010}}</ref> However, according to one source, Lee admitted he eats fish, indicating a [[pescatarian]] diet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vegetarianstar.com/2008/09/22/should-ben-lee-be-de-throned|title=Vegetarian StarShould Ben Lee Be De-Throned?|website=Vegetarianstar.com|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! colspan=\"1\"| Peak\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Certification\n|-\n! style=\"font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\">Peaks in Australia:\n* Top 50 peaks: {{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ben+Lee|title=australian-charts.com \u2013 Discography Ben Lee|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=29 July 2016}}\n* Top 100 peaks to December 2010: {{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}\n* \"Nothing Much Happens\": {{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/q1abuq2.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received 24 May 2016|publisher=Imgur.com|accessdate=26 November 2016}}\n* ''Love Is the Great Rebellion'': {{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-florence-the-machine-debuts-at-no-1-20150606|title=ARIA Albums: Florence + The Machine Debuts at No 1|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=6 June 2015|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Grandpaw Would]]''\n|\n* Released: 22 June 1